TY  - JOUR
AU  - Jalapathy, P
AU  - Unnissa, MM
TI  - Revolutionizing sustainability and adoption of blockchain technology: A dual-channel approach to (Re)manufacturing strategy with an extended warranty
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - The rapid evolution of internet technology and E-Commerce platforms has significantly transformed supply chain management, prompting original equipment manufacturers to investigate (re)manufacturing practices for both environmental and economic advantages. This study develops a Stackelberg game-theoretic framework to ascertain optimal strategies for the adoption of blockchain technology and the selection of distribution channels with extended warranties. Two closed-loop supply chain models are analyzed: one that excludes (re)manufacturing and another that incorporates it. Despite the economic and sustainability benefits associated with remanufactured products, consumer willingness to purchase such items remains limited. Consequently, manufacturers are exploring blockchain technology as a mechanism to enhance product information transparency, foster trust, and improve consumer purchase intentions. The proposed framework effectively captures the strategic interactions between manufacturers and traditional retailers, considering production costs, retail channel expenses, demand sensitivities, and the ratio of high-quality product returns. Numerical analysis indicates that manufacturers should consider adopting blockchain when consumer value discounts for remanufactured products are significant and when the related implementation costs are manageable across both E-Commerce and traditional retail channels. The findings further suggest that the integration of blockchain adoption, optimal channel strategies, and warranty offerings can enhance the profitability of closed-loop supply chains while simultaneously promoting sustainability.
