TY  - JOUR
AU  - Maddah, HA
TI  - Evaluating treatment units for the optimization of large textile WWTPs: A game theoretic approach
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT
AB  - Textile companies generate significant wastewater rich in dyes and organic acids, posing a threat to surface and groundwater quality if untreated. This study employs a game-theoretic (GT) approach using backward induction to optimize the removal of total suspended solids (TSS) and total dissolved solids (TDS) in wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs). The research identifies effective strategies for unit selection by analyzing interactions among pseudo-passive treatment units. Mass balances precede the GT algorithm for a flowrate of Q(in) = 60 mgd, characteristics TSSin = 440 mg/L, and TDSin = 7800 mg/L. Results show a potential flow recovery of 75% and TSS removal efficiency of 99.99%. The Screening/Oil-Removal (SR/OR), Sedimentation (SD), and Sand/GAC-Filter (SGF) units maximize TSS removal. The normalized summation (NS) method suggests a 50% reduction in required units, enhancing cost efficiency. A critical relationship was identified between R% and the selection of units. The GT analysis reveals that maximizing TSS requires only four units [SR -> SD1 -> SD2 -> SGF], achieving rejections between 65 and 170%/mgd, minimizing unnecessary costs, while TDS removal follows a different configuration [OR -> RM-FL -> ON -> OZ], achieving expected removal rates of 22.68%. Based on normalization, the OZ unit is the optimal choice for achieving a high TDS & lowast;-R%, with an estimated rejection of 45%/mgd. The GT algorithm further optimized unit selection with >50% fewer units, potentially enhancing Nitrate-N removal N & lowast; = N%/Q(out)> 80%/mgd via TSS-R%-Max design. This research demonstrates the effective integration of non-cooperative game models into WWTP design, improving treatment efficiency and sustainability.
