TY  - JOUR
AU  - Zheng, BR
AU  - Yu, N
AU  - Jin, L
AU  - Xia, HS
TI  - Effects of power structure on manufacturer encroachment in a closed-loop supply chain
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - Whether manufacturers encroach upon the retail channel or not is of great importance for both the manufacturers themselves and downstream retailers. In this paper, we consider a closed-loop supply chain (CLSC) comprised of a manufacturer who faces the decision of introducing the direct channel, and a retailer who manages the retail channel. We use a game theory framework to investigate the manufacturer's encroachment strategy and its effects on the performance of the retailer and supply chain system in different power structures (manufacturer-Stakelberg, retailer-Stakelberg and Nash). The results show that in the symmetric initial demand case, regardless of which power structure is in place, the manufacturer always prefers encroachment, whereas the retailer can only benefit when the degree of channel competition is not intense. Furthermore, the manufacturer prefers the power structure of manufacturer-Stakelberg, Nash and retailer-Stakelberg in turn as the degree of channel competition increases; the optimal interval in which the retailer benefiting from the encroachment is the widest under the manufacturer-Stakelberg game. Finally, we extend the model to the asymmetric initial demand case and find that encroachment may also leads to a "lose-lose" outcome for the manufacturer and the retailer, which depends on the degree of channel competition and the value of the initial demand.
