AU  - Jafari, H
TI  - Sustainable development by reusing of recyclables in a textile industry including two collectors and three firms: A game-theoretic approach for pricing decisions
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Nowadays, due to reducing the natural resource of cotton, textile industries attempt to find substitutable resources for it. In this point of view, some recyclables like the plastic and metal bottles have been recognized to be appropriate substitutable materials for cotton. These recyclables can be collected, cleaned, fragmented, and reused in such industries. In this study, a supply chain structure is established including two collectors and three firms. The collectors collect the plastic and metal bottles separately, whereas the firms clean and fragment them. Two of the firms process only one type of the bottles, while another one has been simultaneously equipped with these two technologies. In the market, some suppliers buy the non-processed materials from the collectors and then clean and fragment them themselves, while others prefer to purchase the cleaned and fragmented materials from the firms. In fact, the suppliers' demands for the processed and non-processed materials are specified based on the prices set in the channels. In this setting, the game-theoretic approach including Nash, Stackelberg, Centralized, and Chain-to-chain models is applied to set the prices under the considered structure. The results indicate that Chain-to-chain game gives the lowest prices, while the highest prices are obtained from Centralized game when a threshold is met. The suppliers prefer to be established Chain-to-chain game among the members. Moreover, the lowest profits for the collectors and the firms are respectively obtained from Nash and Stackelberg games, whereas Centralized game leads to the highest profits for the members and the whole system. (C) 2019 Published by Elsevier Ltd.
