AU  - Widjaja, M
TI  - How do palm oil mill balance biomass energy conversion and farmer profits allocation? A game-theoretical perspective
T2  - ENVIRONMENT DEVELOPMENT AND SUSTAINABILITY
AB  - Nowadays, the urgency to reduce waste has forced palm oil mills to convert their biomass by-product into energy utilization. Palm oil mills must align edible oil production with the biomass energy market and cost structure. They also have to consider fair benefit allocation to palm oil farmers. This study aims to build a game-theoretical model for palm oil mills and farmers considering biomass energy conversion and investigate the effect of market and cost structure changes on the solutions. Two types of inverse demand for edible oil and biomass energy are utilized and related to one another. The game-theoretical models are formulated under the Stackelberg and profit-sharing schemes. The study discovered that both palm oil mill and farmer produce higher edible oil, biomass energy, and profits if they commit to the profit-sharing scheme with a specific profit portion value for fair profit allocation. Another finding shows that both palm oil mill and farmer payoffs are affected mostly by the biomass energy market and biomass conversion cost structure.
