AU  - WAGNER, T
TI  - PERISHABLE GOODS AND MARKET WASTE
T2  - JAHRBUCH FUR SOZIALWISSENSCHAFT
AB  - Optimal inventory policy is discussed in a one-stage model for a risk neutral profit maximizing firm producing a perishable good with respect to an uncertain demand. If demand is less than the amount stocked, the firm will sell part of the excess supply at the secondary market rate, given the incorporated reuse-rate of the product. For the disposal of the non-reusable rest, called the ''market-waste'', the firm has to pay a tax. First the reaction of the price taking firm to changes in the exogeneous variables is analyzed. If the firm has a monopoly, it will respond to an increase in market-waste tax by cutting its price and the amount stocked. A higher secondary price causes a higher stock and a higher monopoly price for the amount sold. Finally it is shown that in case of several firms which behave as price takers with market shares depending on the stock of the individual firm relative to the amount stocked by all firms, a small number of big suppliers will in a Nash-equilibrium cause a bigger amount of market-waste than a growing number of small suppliers.
