AU  - Li, SX
TI  - Environmental Study on the Optimal Allocation of Water Resources under the Joint Actions of Government and Market - A Case of Tianjin in China
T2  - EKOLOJI
AB  - Environmental economics is an area of economics dealing with the relationship between economy and environment. Environmental economists study the economics of natural resources from both sides - their extraction and use, and the waste products returned to the environment. With the rapid economic development and the accelerating urbanization, a rapid increase in water demand and severe extreme ecological climatic events in recent years has increased the pressure on water supplies throughout most parts of China especially in Beijing Tianjin Hebei region, which led to the need for environmental study on the allocation of limited water across different users so as to achieve economic, social and environmental benefits. A major challenge in optimizing the allocation of water resources is dealing with the joint role of the government and market to solve the conflict of different water interests among different users. Thus, the games theory is applied to analyze the effectiveness of government in macroscopic controlling of water market to optimize the water resources allocation by utilizing the initial water rights allocation. A two-stage dynamic game model regarding the most optimal income as the target is established according to the behavior characteristics of water users. The method for solving the market behavior strategies of water users in case of sub-game perfect Nash equilibrium is studied. On this basis, the optimal scheme of initial water rights allocation and water resources rate can be deduced consequently. The methodology is applied to a case in Tianjin in northern China, as a region facing a severe water shortage over years, in order to illustrate the idea of constructing and solving the model.
