AU  - Zhou, YH
AU  - Liu, Y
AU  - Tian, ZH
TI  - Turn the tables: Proactive deception defense decision-making based on Bayesian attack graphs and Stackelberg games
T2  - NEUROCOMPUTING
AB  - As cyberattacks become increasingly sophisticated, traditional defense mechanisms are outmatched against advanced persistent threats (APTs). Active deception defense mechanisms that rely on traditional honeypots have proven to be able to sense threats to a certain extent, but their reliance on statically deployed honeypots leads to the risk of being bypassed and failing to sense covert attackers. In this paper, we address the limitations of traditional deception defense and introduce a new lightweight technique, Honeypoint, which detects hidden unknown threats early by disguising itself as a legitimate service. Further, to address the lack of dynamic changes in deception decoys and the fact that deploying honeypoints without a purpose leads to a great waste of resources and costs. We propose an active deception defense model based on Bayesian attack graph and Stackelberg game (BagSg) for guiding the deployment of honeypots. The Bayesian attack graph helps identify attack paths and vulnerabilities in the network, while the Stackelberg game models the strategic interactions between attackers and defenders, and discusses the impact of deception defense strategies on both regular and advanced attackers in a long-term attack and defense game. Experimental results show that Honeypoint significantly outperforms traditional honeypots in detecting covert attack behavior. Moreover, the deployment efficiency of deception strategies can be optimized by using the BagSg model, revealing the importance of using deception defense strategies consistently in long-term cyber security defense.
