AU  - Zhou, Y
AU  - Xiong, Y
AU  - Jin, MY
TI  - The entry of third-party remanufacturers and its impact on original equipment manufacturers in a two-period game-theoretic model
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - From the perspective of original equipment manufacturers (OEMs), the conventional wisdom is that in-house remanufacturing is beneficial, and third-party remanufacturing is detrimental. In this paper, we demonstrate that conventional wisdom can be reversed when an incumbent OEM faces the possible entry of a competing OEM. We formulate the market competition over a two-period horizon. The incumbent OEM is the sole seller during the first period. End-of-use products could be remanufactured by the incumbent OEM (i.e., in-house remanufacturing), or by an independent remanufacturer (i.e., third-party remanufacturing). We find that in-house remanufacturing indeed increases the incumbent's profit because of the effect of market segmentation. Moreover, third-party remanufacturing can also be beneficial because of the effect of entry deterrence. If and only if the new production cost is sufficiently low, the effect of entry deterrence associated with third-party remanufacturing outperforms the effect of market segmentation associated with in-house remanufacturing from the incumbent's perspective. This paper provides a novel explanation for the prevalence of third-party remanufacturing: it may reduce incumbent OEMs' profits, but it protects them from more significant losses caused by the entry of competing OEMs. Therefore, under certain conditions, incumbent OEMs should facilitate third-party remanufacturing even if it is detrimental. (c) 2020 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
