TI  - Dynamic suitability site selection and policy pathway for decommissioned photovoltaic recycling in China: Integrating spherical fuzzy sets and dynamic computable general equilibrium model
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Driven by global energy transition and Sustainable Development Goals, photovoltaic (PV) capacity has expanded rapidly. However, this growth has simultaneously created formidable challenges in managing decommissioned PV recycling. This study constructs a latitude-longitude level spatiotemporal database of China's decommissioned PV by 2040 using a geographic information system. Thereby clarifies the spatiotemporal distribution of decommissioned PV to establish a research foundation for subsequent studies. Improved integrated multimachine learning models predict key indicators to enhance assessment precision. Based on this, it dynamically evaluates recycling site suitability across four phases from 2028 to 2040. An integrated model supports this evaluation: Spherical Fuzzy Set (SFS) handles uncertainty; Analytic hierarchy process and Criteria importance through intercriteria correlation determine subjective and objective weights, fused via game theory combination weight method; SFS-Multi-attribute based analytic compromise quantifies suitability. A dynamic computable general equilibrium model assesses the impacts of Research and Development (R&D) subsidy policies from 2020 to 2050 for the decommissioned PV industry on energy structure, carbon emissions, and economic growth. Results reveal that decommissioned PV exhibits a west-to-east shift, with northwest regions dominated by largescale centralized PV and east regions by distributed PV. Suitability is shaped by transportation and economy beyond decommissioned volume. The score difference between the points in the dynamic assessment and those in the static assessment is 1.4 %. R&D subsidies demonstrate diminishing marginal returns when increased beyond 20 % of baseline levels, with optimal effectiveness at moderate levels. This study contributes to advancing the sustainable production and management of decommissioned PV on a global scale.
