TY  - JOUR
AU  - Zhu, RQ
AU  - Zeng, XD
AU  - Xia, XQ
TI  - Assessing the differential effects: differentiated vs. progressive carbon tax on authorized remanufacturing systems
T2  - ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ASSESSMENT REVIEW
AB  - As sustainable development progresses, the uniform carbon tax is no longer sufficient to balance environmental and economic goals. Given the varying emissions across industries and products, along with the regressive nature of carbon taxes, both differentiated and progressive tax approaches have gained importance. However, most existing studies focus on the effects of uniform carbon taxation, offering little comparison between differentiated and progressive tax systems. This gap leaves manufacturers without clear guidance when faced with different tax policies. To address this, the paper uses an authorized remanufacturing model to examine how original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) and authorized remanufacturers (ARs) adjust their production and sales strategies under differentiated and progressive tax systems. The study builds a stackelberg game model to analyze shifts in economic, environmental, and social welfare factors, revealing the distinct strategies of OEMs and ARs in response to each tax policy. The findings indicate that no single carbon tax strategy is universally optimal. When the difference in tax rates between new and remanufactured products is within a certain range, progressive taxation expands the market and increases transactions for both product types. In contrast, under the differentiated tax system, AR profits reach their peak, while OEM revenues decline, and environmental and consumer welfare are maximized. Additionally, consumer preferences for low-carbon products significantly influence the effectiveness of carbon tax policies. In the progressive tax model, an increase in consumer preference directly boosts AR profits. While in the differentiated model, it indirectly enhances OEM profits. Finally, simulation results show that item emissions play a crucial role in selecting the appropriate tax policy. In particular, when new items have higher emissions, progressive taxation offers greater flexibility in adjusting to production scale variations.
