TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chen, Y
AU  - Sun, XT
TI  - Strategic Decisions for Final Product Assembly in 3-D Printing Supply Chains: A Supply Chain Positioning Perspective
T2  - IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON ENGINEERING MANAGEMENT
AB  - A supply chain system comprises both upstream and downstre am members, and in many contexts, a final product assembly (FPA) step is required before products reach the market. Deciding whether and when this FPA step should be undertaken by upstream or downstream supply chain members has become a practical and timely challenge, particularly as 3-D printing technologies now enable and support flexible FPA processes. In this article, we tackle this critical question by developing analytical models grounded in game theory. In our basic model, we consider a supply chain with a single supplier and a single retailer selling a seasonal product. The FPA step incurs costs that vary depending on which supply chain agent performs the task. Our analysis reveals that, from the perspective of the entire supply chain system, the optimal assignment of FPA responsibility is uniquely determined by the respective FPA costs of the members. To achieve this optimal supply chain outcome, we need to identify the best-suited member to undertake the FPA process and coordinate the supply chain accordingly. To this end, we propose the use of a buyback contract and analytically derive its contract bounds. To generate further insights and demonstrate the robustness of our results, we extend our analysis to cover two additional scenarios: markets with two products and contexts where the retailer offers make-to-order services for FPA. Our findings confirm that the core results from the baseline model remain valid while also yielding several new insights. We believe that the results of this study not only make substantial contributions to the literature on supply chain systems but also offer actionable guidance to practitioners and systems' engineers on how to optimally decide which agent should assume the FPA task within supply chain systems. Managerial Relevance Statement-This research provides crucial and actionable insights for engineering managers overseeing manufacturing operations and policymakers seeking to optimize supply chain efficiency and flexibility in the 3-D printing era through strategic final product assembly (FPA) decisions. Engineering managers directly benefit by learning that FPA responsibility should be assigned solely based on comparative assembly costs between suppliers and retailers. By implementing the recommended buyback contracts, engineering managers can achieve near-centralized performance to enhance order quantities and minimize total system costs. Specifically, engineering managers can evaluate FPA cost structures and refine contract designs to balance supplier-retailer incentives and motivate better operational alignment and risk management. Complementary strategies include investing in 3-D printing technologies and adopting make-to-order (MTO) models for retailers, which reduce unsold inventory and drive profitability gains. For policymakers, our research offers insightful guidance to foster industrial innovation through targeted incentives for cost-reducing technologies, particularly accelerating 3-D printing adoption. In addition, the study's insights into buyback and risk-sharing contracts provide an evidence base for policies aimed at enhancing supply chain resilience, especially for seasonal and innovative products. Notably, the research reveals several counterintuitive findings with significant practical implications. First, even with identical FPA costs, retailers employing MTO outperform those using make-to-stock modes, underscoring the value of demand-driven production in dynamic markets.
   Second, well-structured buyback contracts effectively mitigate double marginalization in retailer-led FPA, challenging the perception of decentralized systems as inherently inefficient. For policymakers, a key revelation is that suppliers can strategically reclaim FPA roles by leveraging 3-D printing to reduce costs below critical thresholds, identified in multiproduct analyses. The most impactful finding reveals that, in MTO contexts, retailers should retain FPA even with moderately higher costs than suppliers, overturning traditional cost-minimization paradigms. This shift is justified by systemic benefits, such as enhanced demand responsiveness and reduced waste. Collectively, this research equips managers with validated frameworks to reconfigure assembly networks profitably while guiding policymakers in designing interventions that accelerate cost-efficient production via 3-D printing technologies.
